      class="w-full h-64 md:h-80 object-cover"
    />
  </div>

  <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    <h2>The Critical Adhesive Decision</h2>
    
    <p>
      Adhesive selection is one of the most critical decisions in cemented footwear manufacturing. The adhesive system determines bond strength, durability, processing requirements, and ultimately the performance of the finished product. Understanding adhesive technology enables informed selection for specific applications.
    </p>

    <h2>Polyurethane Adhesives</h2>
    
    <h3>Technology Overview</h3>
    <p>
      Polyurethane (PU) adhesives dominate footwear cemented construction due to their excellent balance of performance characteristics.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Moisture Cure:</strong> PU adhesives cure by reacting with atmospheric moisture.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Chemical Structure:</strong> Isocyanate groups react with water to form polyurethane linkages.
    </p>

    <h3>Performance Characteristics</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Bond Strength:</strong> Excellent bond strength to most footwear materials.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Flexibility:</strong> Cured PU remains flexible, accommodating sole flexing.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Substrate Compatibility:</strong> Bonds effectively to both porous and non-porous materials.
    </p>

    <h3>Application Requirements</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Humidity Control:</strong> Cure rate depends on atmospheric humidity.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Coverage Rates:</strong> Typically 80-150 g/m² depending on porosity.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Activation Temperature:</strong> Usually 60-70°C for heat activation.
    </p>

    <h2>Chloroprene Adhesives</h2>
    
    <h3>Technology Overview</h3>
    <p>
      Chloroprene (neoprene) adhesives provide distinctive performance characteristics valued in specific applications.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Solvent-Based:</strong> Traditional chloroprene adhesives dissolved in organic solvents.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Rubber Base:</strong> Polychloroprene polymer provides rubber-like properties.
    </p>

    <h3>Performance Characteristics</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Initial Grab:</strong> Excellent green tack provides rapid initial bonding.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Heat Resistance:</strong> Good resistance to heat during activation.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Flexibility:</strong> Good flexibility after cure.
    </p>

    <h3>Application Considerations</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Solvent Flash-Off:</strong> Longer drying time for solvent evaporation.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Ventilation Requirements:</strong> Solvent content requires adequate ventilation.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Storage Stability:</strong> Generally good shelf life.
    </p>

    <h2>Water-Based Adhesives</h2>
    
    <h3>Environmental Drivers</h3>
    <p>
      Environmental regulations increasingly favor water-based adhesive alternatives to reduce VOC emissions.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Polymer Dispersions:</strong> Water-based PU and acrylic dispersions.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Meets increasingly strict environmental standards.
    </p>

    <h3>Performance Considerations</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Bond Strength:</strong> Can match solvent-based performance when properly formulated.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Processing Differences:</strong> Requires different drying parameters.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Cost Implications:</strong> Higher material costs potentially offset by compliance benefits.
    </p>

    <h2>Selection Criteria</h2>
    
    <h3>Material Compatibility</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Rubber Bonding:</strong> All adhesive types bond rubber effectively.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>PU Midsoles:</strong> May require primer for optimal adhesion.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>TPU Materials:</strong> Often require surface treatment or primer.
    </p>

    <h3>Performance Requirements</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Dynamic Loading:</strong> High-performance applications require PU adhesives.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Heat Resistance:</strong> Elevated temperature exposure favors chloroprene.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Water Exposure:</strong> Wet conditions require specific formulation selection.
    </p>

    <h3>Processing Considerations</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Equipment Compatibility:</strong> Verify adhesive works with existing equipment.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Environmental Conditions:</strong> Humidity and temperature affect cure.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Production Speed:</strong> Different adhesives suit different production volumes.
    </p>

    <h2>China Manufacturing</h2>
    
    <h3>Adhesive Availability</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Local Supply:</strong> Major adhesive manufacturers have China production.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Technical Support:</strong> Local technical support available from suppliers.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Import Options:</strong> Premium adhesives available through import channels.
    </p>

    <h3>Sourcing Considerations</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Specification Clarity:</strong> Define adhesive type, coverage, and performance requirements.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Certification Requirements:</strong> Verify compliance with target market regulations.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      <strong>Testing Protocol:</strong> Establish testing procedures for adhesive performance.
    </p>
  </div>
